S'  We analyse the nature of the statistics of the work done on or by a quantum\nmany-body system brought out of equilibrium. We show that, for the sudden\nquench, it is in general possible to retrieve the whole non-equilibrium\nthermodynamics via single projective measurements of observables. We highlight\nin a physically clear way the qualitative implications for the statistics of\nwork coming from considering processes described by operators that either\ncommute or do not commute with the unperturbed Hamiltonian of a given system.\nWe consider a quantum many-body system and derive an expression that allows us\nto give a physical interpretation to all of the cumulants of the work in the\ncase of quenched operators commuting with the unperturbed Hamiltonian. In the\ncommuting case the observables that we need to measure have an intuitive\nphysical meaning. Conversely in the non-commuting case, irrespectively of the\nsize of the quench, we show that it is possible to operate still with single\nprojective measurements but we derive an explicit expression for all the\ncumulants of the work that shows that physical properties are not so simply\ndecoded from those quantities. This circumstance makes the study of the physics\nof the system non-trivial as well as the emergence of thermodynamics from the\nfully quantum microscopic description. Interested in the criticality of a\nmany-body system, we illustrate our ideas with the example of the Ising model\nin a transverse field.\n'
