S'  We report on the noise spectrum experienced by few nanometer deep\nnitrogen-vacancy (NV) centers in diamond as a function of depth, surface\ncoating, magnetic ?eld and temperature. Analysis reveals a double-Lorentzian\nnoise spectra consistent with a surface electronic spin bath, with slower\ndynamics due to spin-spin interactions and faster dynamics related to phononic\ncoupling. These results shed new light on the mechanisms responsible for\nsurface noise a?ecting shallow spins at semiconductor interfaces, and suggests\npossible directions for further studies. We demonstrate dynamical decoupling\nfrom the surface noise, paving the way to applications ranging from nanoscale\nNMR to quantum networks.\n'
